<TITLE> Japan ruling bloc wins Osaka governor poll: media </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TOKYO, Jan 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A celebrity lawyer backed by Japan's ruling bloc was certain to win Sunday's poll for governor of Osaka, media said, in a rare bit of cheer for the government as a feisty opposition pushes for an early general election. Toru Hashimoto, backed by Prime Minister Yasuo Fukuda's Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and its junior coalition partner, was assured victory over four other candidates running for governor of the western Japanese prefecture, Kyodo news agency and TV broadcaster NHK said, citing exit polls and early returns. Pre-election surveys had given Hashimoto, 38, the lead over his main rival, Sadatoshi Kumagai, 63, a graduate school professor backed by the opposition Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ) and two smaller allies, but had also shown many voters were undecided. The Democrats and their allies, who control parliament's upper house and can delay legislation, are pushing for an early election for the powerful lower house in hopes of ousting the long-ruling LDP. Fukuda's popularity has slid on doubts about his leadership since the 71-year-old moderate took office last September, and a recent newspaper survey showed almost half of Japanese voters wanted the Democrats to win the next general election. A ruling camp defeat in Osaka would have been another troubling omen for Fukuda's coalition, analysts said. The Democrats campaigned hard for Kumagai, with DPJ leader Ichiro Ozawa even skipping a vote on a bill to resume Japan's controversial naval mission in support of US-led operations in Afghanistan to dash off to speak in Osaka instead. Hashimoto, however, attracted support from a large chunk of voters unaffiliated with any party, a group whose clout has been growing in recent years, media said. "A well-known figure in Japan's media, he succeeded in reaching out to voters not affiliated with political parties as well as LDP and New Komeito supporters," Kyodo reported. Hashimoto's candidacy was in line with a trend among 